\par \pard\plain \s27\sb120\widctlpar\tx270 \b\f5\fs18 Using Apache modules in C++Builder 6
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar\tx270 \f4\fs20 
\par The following two steps are required when using Apache DSOs in C++Builder 6 [note: this requirement does {\i not} apply to Apache DSOs in Delphi 6]. 
\par 
\par \pard\plain \s17\fi-450\li450\widctlpar\tx450 \f4\fs20 1.\tab Choose Project|Options, then the Packages tab. Uncheck the "Build with runtime packages" checkbox. 
\par 
\par 2.\tab To load Apache modules, you must insert an underscore ("_") as the first character of any module symbols in the LoadModule entry of your http.conf file.
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar\tx270 \f4\fs20  
\par Example:
\par 
\par If, for example, you export a module named hello_module and set the content type to hello-handler in your project source file, as shown here:
\par 
\par \pard\plain \s15\widctlpar\tx270 \f11\fs20 {\cs29 //------------------------------------------------------}
\par extern "C"
\par \{
\par   Httpd::module __declspec(dllexport) hello_module;
\par \}
\par 
\par int WINAPI DllEntryPoint(HINSTANCE hinst, 
\par \tab unsigned long reason, void*)
\par \{
\par   try
\par   \{
\par     if (reason == DLL_PROCESS_ATTACH) \{
\par \tab \tab Apacheapp::set_module(&hello_module);
\par \tab \tab strcpy(Apacheapp::ContentType, "hello-handler");
\par \tab \tab Application->Initialize();
\par \tab \tab Application->CreateForm(__classid(TWebModule1),
\par \tab \tab \tab &WebModule1);
\par \tab \tab Application->Run();
\par     \}
\par   \}
\par   catch (Exception &exception)
\par   \{
\par   \}
\par   return 1;
\par \}
\par {\cs29 //------------------------------------------------------}
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar\tx270 \f4\fs20 
\par You would need to modify your http.conf file as follows:
\par 
\par \pard\plain \s15\widctlpar\tx270 \f11\fs20 #############################################
\par LoadModule _hello_module modules/Hello.dll
\par <Location /hello>
\par         SetHandler hello-handler
\par </Location>
\par ##############################################
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar\tx270 \f4\fs20 
\par \pard\plain \s27\sb120\widctlpar\tx270 \b\f5\fs18 Using ClearModuleList in Apache httpd.conf
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar\tx270 \f4\fs20 
\par ClearModuleList, enabled by default in Apache 1.3.22 and later (it was previously commented out), offers you two options when developing modules in C++Builder. The command appears between the LoadModule and AddModule lines in httpd.conf:
\par 
\par \pard\plain \s15\widctlpar\tx270 \f11\fs20 \tab LoadModule foo_module modules/mod_foo.dll
\par \tab ...
\par {\b \tab ClearModuleList}
\par \tab ...
\par \tab AddModule mod_foo.c
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar\tx270 \f4\fs20 
\par To use the command, either:
\par  
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f1\fs20 \'b7\tab}\pard\plain \s26\fi-173\li173\widctlpar\tx180\tx270{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\pnf1\pnstart1\pnindent173\pnhang{\pntxtb \'b7}}\f4\fs20 Add your "LoadModule" command {\i after} the ClearModuleList line in httpd.conf.
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar\tx270 \f4\fs20 {\b\i or}
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f1\fs20 \'b7\tab}\pard\plain \s26\fi-173\li173\widctlpar\tx180\tx270{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\pnf1\pnstart1\pnindent173\pnhang{\pntxtb \'b7}}\f4\fs20 \tab In your C++Builder project file, change your module name using the strcopy function:

\par \pard\plain \s15\widctlpar\tx270 \f11\fs20 \tab 
\par \tab strcpy(ModuleName, "MyModuleName");
\par \pard\plain \s16\fi-270\li270\widctlpar\tx270 \f4\fs20 \tab \tab 
\par \tab Then use the existing LoadModule/AddModule sections in httpd.conf, specifying your new module name:
\par 
